Dr. Hammond's presentation led on to discussing the importance of characterising variable immune gene complexes including repetitive immune gene complexes, highlighting research on KIR and MHC genes. Dr Hammond emphasized that at present the human genome is used as a gold standard for research and there remains many gaps in livestock genome assembly and annotation. Of greatest scrutiny and target of improvement are the often variable genes associated with reproduction and the immune system. Further research should consider the quality of reference genomes used.</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Professional Practitioners</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.vetvaccnet.ac.uk/news/2015/11/veterinary-vaccinology-network-bioinformatics-workshop</gtr:url><gtr:year>2015</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>internal seminar - NKC evolution</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>Local</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>1E33F5DD-1C4F-42E4-8D6B-6437679BEB73</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Conveyed and discussed our current research to peers at The Pirbright Institute.</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Other audiences</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2016</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>invited seminar - sequencing immune gene complexes - University of Minnesota</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>International</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>AD8BD821-108D-43A4-88ED-88B4CD768278</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Discussed current work using new reference genomes to characterise immune gene complexes</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Postgraduate students</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2016</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOu